tle=[[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]|years=1999\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Schoomaker]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Peake]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert A. McDonald]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecVA}}\n{{US Army Chiefs of Staff}}\n{{Obama cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shinseki, Eric}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American amputees]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American members of the Cabinet of the United States]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Honeywell people]]\n[[Category:Landmine victims]]\n[[Category:National War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Obama administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:People from Kauai County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:People from Lihue, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Coast Guard Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Army Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:United States Army Command and General Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Army Vice Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Veterans Affairs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Council]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Eric Shinseki\n|image        = Eric Shinseki official Veterans Affairs portrait.jpg\n|office       = 7th [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]]\n|president    = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy       = [[W. Scott Gould]]<br/>[[Sloan D. Gibson]]\n|term_start   = January 21, 2009\n|term_end     = May 30, 2014\n|predecessor  = [[James Peake]]\n|successor    = [[Bob McDonald (businessman)|Bob McDonald]]\n|office1      = 34th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]\n|president1   = [[Bill Clinton]]<br/>[[George W. Bush]]\n|term_start1  = June 21, 1999\n|term_end1    = June 11, 2003\n|predecessor1 = [[Dennis Reimer]]\n|successor1   = [[Peter Schoomaker]]\n|office2      = 28th [[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]\n|president2   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start2  = November 24, 1998\n|term_end2    = June 21, 1999\n|predecessor2 = [[William W. Crouch]]\n|successor2   = [[Jack Keane]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1942|11|28}}\n|birth_place  = [[Lihue, Hawaii]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|spouse       = Patricia Shinseki\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[United States Military Academy]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br/>[[Duke University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n|allegiance   = United States\n|branch       = [[United States Army]]\n|rank         = [[General (United States)|General]]\n|serviceyears = 1965\u20132003\n|commands     = [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[Seventh United States Army]]<br/>[[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe|Allied Land Forces Central Europe]]<br/>[[SFOR|NATO Stabilization Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]<br/>[[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]]<br/>2nd Brigade, [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Infantry Division]]<br/>3rd Squadron, [[7th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|7th Cavalry Regiment]], 3rd Infantry Division<br/>3rd Squadron, [[5th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|5th Cavalry Regiment]], [[9th Infantry Division (United States)|9th Infantry Division]]\n|battles      = [[Vietnam War]]<br/>[[Bosnian War]]\n|mawards      = [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Air Force Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Coast Guard)|Coast Guard Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (2)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Purple Heart]] (2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/search.php?term=shinseki |title=Award citations, Eric Ken Shinseki |website=Hall of Valor |publisher=Military Times |accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://armyhistory.org/general-eric-k-shinseki/ |title=Biography, General Eric K. Shinseki |website=Campaign for the National Museum of the United States Army |publisher=Army Historical Foundation |accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Eric Ken Shinseki''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u1d7b|n|\u02c8|s|\u025b|k|i}}; born November 28, 1942) is a retired [[United States Army]] [[General (United States)|general]] who served as the seventh [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]] (2009\u20132014).<ref>{{cite news |last=Jaffe |first=Greg |last2=O'Keefe |first2=Ed |date=May 30, 2014 |title=Obama accepts resignation of VA Secretary Shinseki |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/shinseki-apologies-for-va-health-care-scadal/2014/05/30/e605885a-e7f0-11e3-8f90-73e071f3d637_story.html |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> His final United States Army post was as the 34th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]] (1999\u20132003). Shinseki is a veteran of two tours of combat in the [[Vietnam War]], in which he was awarded three [[Bronze Star Medal]]s for valor and two [[Purple Heart]]s.<ref name=\"May 2009 remarks\">{{cite web | title=Remarks by Secretary Eric K. Shinseki, 2009 Secretary's Awards for Excellence in Nursing | author=Eric Shinseki |publisher=U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs | date=May 12, 2009 | url=http://www.va.gov/opa/speeches/2009/09_0512.asp}}</ref> He was the first Asian-American [[List of United States Army four-star generals|four-star general]], and the first Asian-American Secretary of Veterans Affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/asianpacificamericans/profiles |title=Overseas Contigency Operations Profiles |website=Asia Pacific Americans in the United States Army |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Shinseki 1965.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Shinseki at [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] in 1965]]\nShinseki was born in [[Lihue, Hawaii|Lihue]], [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]], in the then [[Territory of Hawaii]], to an American family of [[Japanese diaspora|Japanese ancestry]]. [[Sansei|His grandparents emigrated]] from [[Hiroshima]] to Hawaii in 1901.<ref>Obata, Hiroshi. [http://www.hiroshimapeacemedia.jp/mediacenter/article.php?story=20090130144958922_ja \u4e21\u7956\u7236\u6bcd\u306f\u5e83\u5cf6\u51fa\u8eab] (\"Shinseki: both grandparents are from Hiroshima\"). ''Hiroshima Peace Media'' (Japan). January 30, 2009</ref> He grew up in a [[sugarcane]] [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|plantation]] community on Kaua'i and graduated from [[Kauai High School|Kaua'i High and Intermediate School]] in 1960.<ref name=\"USNWR18DEC2008\" /> While attending Kaua'i he was active in the [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scouts]] and served as [[class president]].<ref name=\"USNWR18DEC2008\" /> As a boy, Shinseki learned that three of his uncles had served in the [[442nd Infantry Regiment]], a unit of Japanese Americans that became one of the most decorated fighting units in United States history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eric K. Shinseki|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1502787/Eric-K-Shinseki|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> Motivated by his uncles' example, he attended the [[United States Military Academy]] and graduated in 1965 with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree and a commission as a [[Second Lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]]. He earned a [[Master of Arts]] degree in [[English Literature]] from [[Duke University]]. He was also educated at the [[Armor Branch (United States)|Armor]] Officer Advanced Course, the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]], and the [[National War College]] of [[National Defense University]].\n\n<div style=\"clear: left;\">\n\n==Military service==\n[[File:EricShinseki.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Shinseki as the Chief of Staff of the Army]]\n[[File:Gen Eric Shinseki official portrait.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A 2003 portrait of Shinseki]]\nShinseki served in a variety of command and staff assignments in the Continental United States and overseas, including two combat [[Tour of duty|tours]] with the [[9th Infantry Division (United States)|9th]] and [[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th]] Infantry Divisions in the [[South Vietnam|Republic of Vietnam]] as an [[Artillery observer#Forward Observers in the US Army/Marine Corps|artillery forward observer]] and as commander of Troop A, 3rd Squadron, [[5th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|5th Cavalry Regiment]] during the [[Vietnam War]]. During one of those tours while serving as a forward artillery observer, he stepped on a [[land mine]], which blew the front off one of his feet; after spending almost a year recovering from his injuries, he returned to active duty in 1971.<ref name=\"May 2009 remarks\"/>\n\nShinseki has served at [[Schofield Barracks, Hawai'i]] with Headquarters, [[United States Army Pacific|United States Army Hawaii]], and [[Fort Shafter]] with Headquarters, [[United States Army Pacific]]. He has taught at the U.S. Military Academy's Department of English. During duty with the [[3rd Armored Cavalry Regiment (United States)|3rd Armored Cavalry Regiment]] at [[Fort Bliss]], [[Texas]], he served as the regimental adjutant and as the executive officer of its 1st Squadron.\n\nShinseki's ten-plus years of service in Europe included assignments as Commander, 3rd Squadron, [[7th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|7th Cavalry]], [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Infantry Division]] ([[Schweinfurt]]); Commander, 2nd Brigade, 3rd Infantry Division ([[Kitzingen]]); Assistant Chief of Staff, G3, 3rd Infantry Division (Operations, Plans and Training) (W\u00fcrzburg); and Assistant Division Commander for Maneuver, 3rd Infantry Division (Schweinfurt). The 3rd Division was organized at that time as a heavy [[Armoured warfare|mechanized]] division. He also served as Assistant Chief of Staff, G3 (Operations, Plans, and Training), [[VII Corps (United States)|VII&nbsp;Corps]] ([[Stuttgart]]). Shinseki served as Deputy Chief of Staff for Support, [[Allied Land Forces Southern Europe]] ([[Verona]]), an element of the [[Allied Forces Southern Europe]].\n\nFrom March 1994 to July 1995, Shinseki commanded the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] at [[Fort Hood]], Texas. In July 1996, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]] and became Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations and Plans, United States Army. In June 1997, Shinseki was appointed to the [[Four-star rank|rank of general]] before assuming duties as Commanding General, [[Seventh United States Army]]; Commander, Allied Land Forces Central Europe; and Commander, [[NATO]] [[SFOR|Stabilization Force]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. Shinseki became the Army's 28th [[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Vice Chief of Staff]] on November 24, 1998, then became its 34th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff]] on June 22, 1999.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=May 27, 2006|last=Fahrig|first=Jody T.|url=http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=4731|title=Army welcomes Shinseki as new chief|agency=Army News Service|date=June 23, 1999 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312164047/http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=4731|archivedate=March 12, 2008}}</ref> Shinseki retired on June 11, 2003 at the end of his four-year term. His Farewell Memo contained some of his ideas regarding the future of the military.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eric K|last=Shinseki|url=https://media.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/opinions/documents/shinseki.pdf|title=End of Tour Memorandum|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=June 10, 2003 |accessdate=December 7, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> At that time, General Shinseki retired from the Army after 38 years of military service.\n\n{{As of|2009}}, Shinseki was the highest-ranked [[Asian American]] in the history of the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Second Act for General Shinseki|author=Thom Shanker |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/15/us/politics/15shinseki.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 14, 2009|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> Additionally, as of 2004, he is the highest-ranked [[Japanese American]] to have served in the United States Armed Forces.<ref>{{cite news|title=An Inspiration for a Generation |author=Gregg K. Kakesako|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2004/03/31/news/story3.html|newspaper=[[Honolulu Star Bulletin]] |date=March 31, 2004|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Army Chief of Staff===\n[[File:Senator Thurmond 100th Birthday.jpg|Shinseki as Army Chief of Staff thanks Senator [[Strom Thurmond]] for his service to the country during his 100th birthday celebration. Shinseki joined [[Thomas E. White|Thomas White]] in naming the centerpiece of the National Museum of the Army in Thurmond's honor in a ceremony at his office on Capitol Hill December 4, 2002.|right|thumb]]\nDuring his tenure as Army Chief of Staff, Shinseki initiated an innovative but controversial plan to make the army more strategically deployable and mobile in urban terrain by creating [[Stryker|Stryker Interim-Force Brigade Combat Teams]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Army Takes on Critics of an Armored Vehicle|author=Thom Shanker|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30B14F83E5B0C7A8EDDA90994DA404482|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 29, 2002|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> He conceived a long term strategic plan for the army dubbed \"Objective Force\", which included a program he designed, [[Future Combat Systems]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.ausa.org/WEBINT/DeptAUSANews.nsf/byid/CCRN-6CGLGV|title=Objective Force is Needed for Relevancy|date=April 1, 2001|work=AUSA News|publisher=Association of the United States Army|accessdate=March 20, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509002847/http://www3.ausa.org/WEBINT/DeptAUSANews.nsf/byid/CCRN-6CGLGV|archivedate=May 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> One other controversial plan that Shinseki implemented was the wearing of the black beret for all army personnel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beret battle: Army approves color change |url=http://amarillo.com/stories/2001/03/16/usn_beretbattle.shtml|newspaper=Amarillo Globe=News|date=March 16, 2001|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> Prior to Shinseki implementing this policy, only the [[United States Army Rangers]] could wear the [[black beret]]. When the black beret was given to all soldiers and officers, the Rangers moved to the [[tan beret]].\n\nShinseki publicly clashed with Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] during the planning of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|war in Iraq]] over how many troops the United States would need to keep in Iraq for the postwar occupation of that country. As Army Chief of Staff, Shinseki testified to the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]] on February 25, 2003 that \"something in the order of several hundred thousand soldiers\" would probably be required for postwar Iraq. This was an estimate far higher than the figure being proposed by Secretary Rumsfeld in his invasion plan, and it was rejected in strong language by both Rumsfeld and his [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]], [[Paul Wolfowitz]], who was another chief planner of the invasion and occupation.<ref name=Schmitt2003>{{cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/28/us/threats-responses-military-spending-pentagon-contradicts-general-iraq-occupation.html |title=Pentagon Contradicts General on Iraq Occupation Force's Size|publisher=The New York Times|date=February 28, 2003 |accessdate=April 4, 2012}}</ref> From then on, Shinseki's influence on the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] reportedly waned.<ref>Shanker, Thom [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/12/washington/12shinseki.html \"New Strategy Vindicates Ex-Army Chief Shinseki\"], ''New York Times,'' January 12, 2007.</ref> Critics of the Bush Administration alleged that Shinseki was forced into early retirement as Army Chief of Staff because of his comments on troop levels; however, his retirement was announced nearly a year before those comments.<ref>CNN Political Unit. [http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/10/08/factcheck/ CNN Political Unit debate fact check]. [[CNN.com]]. October 9, 2004.</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|insurgency]] took hold in postwar Iraq, Shinseki's comments and their public rejection by the civilian leadership were often cited by those who felt the Bush administration deployed too few troops to Iraq.<ref name=WashingtonPost_Ricks-Tyson_20061116>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/15/AR2006111500800.html|title=Abizaid Says Withdrawal Would Mean More Unrest|first=Thomas E. |last=Ricks |author2=Ann Scott Tyson|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=November 16, 2006|page=A22|quote=General [Eric] Shinseki was right that a greater international force contribution, U.S. force contribution and Iraqi force contribution should have been available immediately after major combat operations.|accessdate=December 13, 2006}}</ref> On November 15, 2006, in testimony before Congress, [[USCENTCOM|CENTCOM]] Commander General [[John Abizaid]] said that Shinseki had been correct that more troops were needed.<ref name=WashingtonPost_Ricks-Tyson_20061116/>\n\n==Post-military career==\n[[File:Barack Obama signs S.1055 2010-10-05 1.jpg|thumb|right|President Barack Obama and guests at signing of bill to grant [[Congressional Gold Medal]] to [[100th Infantry Battalion (United States)|100th Infantry Battalion]] and [[442nd Infantry Regiment (United States)|442nd Regimental Combat Team]] in recognition of their [[World War II]] service. Shinseki is at the far right.]]\nShinseki has served as a director for several corporations: [[Honeywell International]] and [[Ducommun]], military contractors; [[Grove Farm Corporation]]; [[First Hawaiian Bank]];<ref name=WashingtonPost_Rucker-Ricks_20081207>{{cite news|accessdate=December 7, 2008|title=Shinseki Slated to Head VA, Obama Confirms|first=Philip|last=Rucker|author2=Thomas E. Ricks|work=Washington Post |date=December 6, 2008|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/12/06/shinseki_slated_to_head_va_dem.html?hpid=topnews}}</ref> and [[Guardian Life Insurance]] Company of America.<ref name=ForbesPeople_2008>{{cite news|accessdate=December 7, 2008 |title=Shinseki biography|url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/eric-k-shinseki/41426|work=Forbes}}</ref> He is a member of the Advisory Boards at the [[Center for Public Leadership]], [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], [[Harvard University]], and to the [[U.S. Comptroller General]]. He is a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], the [[Atlantic Council]] of the United States, and the [[Association of the United States Army]].<ref name=PurposePrize_Shinseki_20081207>{{cite web|accessdate=December 7, 2008 |title=The Purpose Prize: Shinseki|url=http://www.purposeprize.org/judges/shinseki.cfm}}</ref>\n\n==United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs (2009\u20132014)==\nOn December 7, 2008, then-[[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Barack Obama]] announced at a [[News conference|press conference]] in [[Chicago]] that he would nominate Shinseki to become the [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]].<ref name=CNN_7_December_2008_Shinseki>{{cite news|accessdate=December 7, 2008 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/07/obama.shinseki/|title=Obama: No one 'more qualified' than Shinseki to head VA |date=December 7, 2008|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Shinseki was unanimously confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on January 20, 2009, and sworn in the next day.<ref name=abrams>{{cite news|last=Abrams|first=Jim|title=Senate confirms 6 cabinet secretaries |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/news/ap/politics/2009/Jan/20/senate_confirms_6_cabinet_secretaries.html|accessdate=January 10, 2013|publisher=Real Clear Politics|date=January 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans Health Administration scandal===\n{{main article|Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014}}\nIn May 2014, Shinseki was embroiled in a scandal involving the [[Veterans Health Administration]], which is a component of the United States Department of Veterans Affairs. Questions involving substandard timely care and false records covering up related timelines had come to light, involving treatment of veterans in a number of veterans hospitals.<ref>[http://us.cnn.com/2014/05/15/politics/va-scandal-eric-shinseki-preview/index.html?hpt=po_c2 Shinseki 'mad as hell' about VA allegations, but won't resign]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140516/NEWS05/305160047/VA-s-top-health-official-resigns-amid-scandal-over-delays-vets-care |title=VA's top health official resigns amid scandal over delays in vets' care &#124; Military Times |publisher=militarytimes.com |date=May 15, 2014 |accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref> On May 30, 2014, President Obama announced that he had accepted Shinseki's resignation as Secretary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/05/30/shinseki-va-veteran-scandal-health-care-delays/9758061/|title=Embattled VA chief Shinseki resigns|publisher=USA Today|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/30/politics/va-hospitals-shinseki/|title=Veterans Secretary Eric Shinseki resigns |publisher=CNN|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> Shinseki said he could not explain the lack of integrity among some leaders in veterans healthcare facilities: \"That breach of integrity is irresponsible, it is indefensible, and unacceptable to me.\" He said he could not defend what happened because it was indefensible, but he could take responsibility for it and he would.<ref name=\"ShinsekiStatement\">{{cite news|title=US president accepts with 'regret' Veterans Affairs chief's resignation|url=http://www.chicagochronicle.com/index.php/sid/222467197/scat/b8de8e630faf3631/ht/US-president-accepts-with-regret-Veterans-Affairs-chiefs-resignation|accessdate=May 31, 2014|work=Chicago Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531144235/http://www.chicagochronicle.com/index.php/sid/222467197/scat/b8de8e630faf3631/ht/US-president-accepts-with-regret-Veterans-Affairs-chiefs-resignation|archive-date=May 31, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Shinseki's resignation was the first time since 2000 that there had not been an Asian American in the [[Cabinet of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mak |first=Tim |date=June 1, 2014 |title=There Are No Asian-Americans In The Cabinet For The First Time Since 2000 |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/06/01/there-are-no-asian-americans-in-the-cabinet-for-the-first-time-since-2000.html |newspaper=The Daily Beast |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n \nIn an interview with retired General [[Peter W. Chiarelli]], journalist [[Robert Siegel]] described the situation as \"a case of a very, very good man who's run up against some pretty terrible problems in his job,\" to which Chiarelli responded, \"I don't look up to any man more than I look up to Eric Shinseki.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Siegel|first=Robert|title=Retired Army Gen. On Shinseki: 'I Don't Look Up To Any Man More'|publisher=NPR|accessdate=May 31, 2014|date=May 30, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/30/317426056/retired-army-gen-on-shinseki-i-dont-look-up-to-any-man-more}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nShinseki is married to his [[Childhood sweetheart|high school sweetheart]], Patricia; they are the parents of two children, Lori and Ken.<ref name=\"USNWR18DEC2008\">{{cite news|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Gen. Eric Shinseki|first=Bobbie Kyle |last=Sauer |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/obama/articles/2008/12/18/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-gen-eric-shinseki|newspaper=U.S. News & World Report|date=December 18, 2008|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref> He also has seven grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shane III |first=Leo |date=June 19, 2013 |title=Shinseki's style: Determined, quiet |url=http://www.stripes.com/shinseki-s-style-determined-quiet-1.226462 |newspaper=Stars and Stripes |access-date=April 9, 2015 }}</ref> \n\n==Awards, decorations, and badges==\nShinseki was awarded the following medals, ribbons, badges, and tabs:<ref name=\"VAbio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.va.gov/opa/bios/bio_shinseki.asp |title=Eric K. Shinseki|work=Office of Public and Intergovernmental Affairs |publisher=United States Department of Veterans Affairs |accessdate=January 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915001346/http://www.va.gov/opa/bios/bio_shinseki.asp |archivedate=September 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/asianpacificsoldiers/history/overseasconops.html |title=Overseas Contingency Operations |work=Asian Pacific Americans in the United States Army |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=January 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140126023258/http://www.army.mil/asianpacificsoldiers/history/overseasconops.html |archivedate=January 26, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/leaders/CSA/csa8X10.jpg |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030429020649/http://www.army.mil/leaders/CSA/csa8X10.jpg |archivedate=April 29, 2003 |title=Chief of Staff of the Army Official Portrait |date=June 24, 2001 |work=Army Leadership |publisher=United States ARmy |accessdate=January 29, 2013 }}<br/>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/108th-congress/senate-resolution/190?q={%22search%22%3A[%22s+res+190%22]}&resultIndex=7 |title=S.RES.190 \u2013 Commending General Eric Shinseki of the United States Army for his outstanding service and commitment to excellence. (Agreed to Senate \u2013 ATS) |website=www.congress.gov |publisher=Library of Congress |quote=Whereas General Shinseki has been awarded the Defense Distinguished Service Medal, Distinguished Service Medal, Legion of Merit (with oak leaf clusters), Bronze Star Medal with 'V' Device (with 2 oak leaf clusters), Purple Heart (with oak leaf cluster), Meritorious Service Medal (with 2 oak leaf clusters), Air Medal, Army Commendation Medal (with oak leaf cluster), Army Achievement Medal, Parachutist Badge, Ranger Tab, Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge, Joint Chiefs of Staff Identification Badge, and the Army Staff Identification Badge; }}</ref>\n{|\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]<ref name=\"Bio\">[http://usgovinfo.about.com/od/thepresidentandcabinet/a/eric_shinseki.htm Eric K. Shinseki: Former Secretary of Veterans Affairs, Department of Veterans Affairs Biography], About.com, U.S. Government, by Robert Longley, last accessed July 13, 2013</ref> (with one oak leaf cluster)<ref name=\"valor\">{{cite news |title=Eric Ken Shinseki |url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=100397 |newspaper=Hall of Valor |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=March 13, 2015 }}<br/>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=Can |date=December 7, 2008 |title=Obama Picks Army Gen. Shinseki To Head VA |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/263183 |newspaper=Digital Journal |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<ref name=\"Bio\"/> (with one oak leaf cluster)<ref name=\"valor\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Navy Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (US Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]<ref name=presidency>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=85040 |title=President-Elect Barack Obama Announces General Eric Shinseki as Secretary of Veterans Affairs |date=December 7, 2008 |website= The American Presidency Project |publisher=UCSB |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Force Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Air Force Distinguished Service Medal]]<ref name=presidency/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Coast Guard Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Coast Guard)|Coast Guard Distinguished Service Medal]]<ref name=presidency/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]] (with Oak Leaf Cluster)<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|other_device=v|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] (with [[\"V\" Device]] and two Oak Leaf Clusters)<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Purple Heart BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Purple Heart]] (with Oak Leaf Cluster)<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] (with two Oak Leaf Clusters)<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Air Medal]]<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]] (with Oak Leaf Cluster)<ref name=\"Bio2\">[http://www.asianamerican.net/bios/General_Shinseki.html General Eric K. Shinseki, Retired Chief of Staff, United States Army], Asian American Network, last accessed July 13, 2014</ref>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Achievement Medal|Army Achievement Medal]]<ref name=\"Bio2\"/>\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|name=National Defense Service Medal ribbon|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] with [[Service star]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=service-star|name=Vietnam Service Ribbon|width=60}}\n|[[Vietnam Service Medal]] with four [[Service star]]s\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Armed Forces Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Armed Forces Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Army Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=NATO Medal Yugoslavia ribbon bar.svg|width=60}}\n|[[NATO Medal]] for Former Yugoslavia\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Vietnam Campaign Medal ribbon with 60- clasp.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Vietnam Campaign Medal]]\n|}\n{|\n|-\n|align=center| [[File:US Army Airborne basic parachutist badge.gif|60px]]\n|[[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|align=center| [[File:Ranger Tab.svg|60px]]\n|[[Ranger Tab]]\n|-\n|align=center| [[File:Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge.png|60px]]