{"title_page": "Jutahy J\u00fanior", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Jutahy J\u00fanior\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es J\u00fanior.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Jutahy J\u00fanior\n| office              = State Representative for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start          = 1979\n| term_end            = 1983\n| office2             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start2         = 1983\n| term_end2           = 1995\n| office3             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start3         = 1999\n| term_end3           = 2019\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|10|14}}\n| birth_place         = [[Salvador]], [[Bahia]], [[Brazil]]\n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} Brazilian\n| spouse              = \n| parents             = Father: [[Juracy Magalh\u00e3es]]\n}}\n'''Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es J\u00fanior''' (born October 14, 1955) is a Brazilian politician, affiliated with the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]] (PSDB).\n\n== Biography ==\nHe is the son of politician [[Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es]] and grandson of Governor [[Juracy Magalh\u00e3es]]. He was a state deputy and is in his sixth term as a federal deputy . In 1994, he was a candidate for the government of Bahia, with the support of [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] and Mayor [[L\u00eddice da Mata]], taking 3rd place.\n\nA lawyer graduated from the [[Federal University of Bahia]] , Jutahy was once a state deputy, a federal constituent deputy, a state secretary for justice and human rights and a minister for social action in the [[Itamar Franco]] government .\n\nJutahy was four times national leader of the PSDB, being the first deputy leader of the bench in the three years in which [[Jos\u00e9 Serra]] assumed the leadership in the Chamber. Married to journalist Jacqueline, he has two children, Jutahy Neto and Lav\u00ednia.\n\nIn 2016, he voted in favor of the impeachment process of then President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/veja-como-deputados-votaram-no-impeachment-de-dilma-na-pec-241-na-reforma-trabalhista-e-na-denuncia-contra-temer.ghtml|title=Veja como deputados votaram no impeachment de Dilma, na PEC 241, na reforma trabalhista e na den\u00fancia contra Temer|website=G1|language=pt-br|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> In April 2017 he voted in favor of Labor Reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/|title=CartaCapital - Jornalismo cr\u00edtico e transparente. Not\u00edcias sobre pol\u00edtica, economia e sociedade com vi\u00e9s progressista|website=CartaCapital|language=pt-BR|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> In August 2017, he voted in favor of the process calling for the opening of an investigation by then President [[Michel Temer]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/politica/como-votou-cada-deputado-sobre-a-denuncia-contra-temer/|title=Como votou cada deputado sobre a den\u00fancia contra Temer|last=CartaCapital|first=Reda\u00e7\u00e3o|date=2017-08-03|website=CartaCapital|language=pt-BR|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018 Brazilian elections|2018 elections]], he was a candidate for the position of senator, but he was in 4th place with about 8% of the valid votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://placar.eleicoes.uol.com.br/2018/1turno/ba/apuracao-no-estado/|title=Senadores e deputados federais/estaduais eleitos: Apura\u00e7\u00e3o e resultado das Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2018 BA|website=UOL Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2018|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Jutahy J\u00fanior\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es J\u00fanior.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Jutahy J\u00fanior\n| office              = State Representative for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start          = 1979\n| term_end            = 1983\n| office2             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start2         = 1983\n| term_end2           = 1995\n| office3             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for [[Bahia]]\n| term_start3         = 1999\n| term_end3           = 2019\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|10|14}}\n| birth_place         = [[Salvador]], [[Bahia]], [[Brazil]]\n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} Brazilian\n| spouse              = \n| parents             = Father: [[Juracy Magalh\u00e3es]]\n}}\n'''Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es J\u00fanior''' (born October 14, 1955) is a Brazilian politician, affiliated with the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]] (PSDB).\n\n== Biography ==\nHe is the son of politician [[Jutahy Magalh\u00e3es]] and grandson of Governor [[Juracy Magalh\u00e3es]]. He was a state deputy and is in his sixth term as a federal deputy . In 1994 , he was a candidate for the government of Bahia , with the support of[[ Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] and Mayor [[L\u00eddice da Mata]], taking 3rd place.\n\nA lawyer graduated from the [[Federal University of Bahia]] , Jutahy was once a state deputy, a federal constituent deputy, a state secretary for justice and human rights and a minister for social action in the [[Itamar Franco]] government .\n\nJutahy was four times national leader of the PSDB, being the first deputy leader of the bench in the three years in which [[Jos\u00e9 Serra]] assumed the leadership in the Chamber. Married to journalist Jacqueline, he has two children, Jutahy Neto and Lav\u00ednia.\n\nIn 2016, he voted in favor of the impeachment process of then President [[Dilma Rousseff]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/veja-como-deputados-votaram-no-impeachment-de-dilma-na-pec-241-na-reforma-trabalhista-e-na-denuncia-contra-temer.ghtml|title=Veja como deputados votaram no impeachment de Dilma, na PEC 241, na reforma trabalhista e na den\u00fancia contra Temer|website=G1|language=pt-br|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>In April 2017 he voted in favor of Labor Reform. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/|title=CartaCapital - Jornalismo cr\u00edtico e transparente. Not\u00edcias sobre pol\u00edtica, economia e sociedade com vi\u00e9s progressista|website=CartaCapital|language=pt-BR|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>In August 2017, he voted in favor of the process calling for the opening of an investigation by then President [[Michel Temer]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartacapital.com.br/politica/como-votou-cada-deputado-sobre-a-denuncia-contra-temer/|title=Como votou cada deputado sobre a den\u00fancia contra Temer|last=CartaCapital|first=Reda\u00e7\u00e3o|date=2017-08-03|website=CartaCapital|language=pt-BR|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018 Brazilian elections|2018 elections]], he was a candidate for the position of senator, but he was in 4th place with about 8% of the valid votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://placar.eleicoes.uol.com.br/2018/1turno/ba/apuracao-no-estado/|title=Senadores e deputados federais/estaduais eleitos: Apura\u00e7\u00e3o e resultado das Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2018 BA|website=UOL Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2018|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Brazil-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_u